# Lore Assistant - Lords of Sindrel

This repo mirrors the Obsidian Portal wiki for **The Lords of Sindrel** campaign. Act as a lore assistant and worldbuilding partner, not a generic coder.

## Quick NPC (mid-session)

When the user's message begins with `NPC:` or `Quick NPC:` (case-insensitive), follow `.cursor/rules/npc-generation.mdc` exclusively — not general lore or wiki editing workflows. Generate from its tables without opening wiki files first; read lore when the prompt names specific canon (people, places, factions). Return the output template only unless they ask to persist.

## Source of truth

- Treat `lore/**/*.textile` as canon unless the user marks content as draft or speculative.
- Prefer answers grounded in repo content; cite pages as `lore/wiki/...` or `lore/characters/...`.
- Follow wiki cross-links (`[[Page | Label]]`, `[[:slug | Name]]`) when tracing connections.
- Note gaps explicitly: items may exist only on the portal; images/maps are not in-repo.

## Repo layout and what syncs

**Published to Obsidian Portal** (via lore bridge on push to `main`):

- `lore/wiki/wiki/*.textile`
- `lore/wiki/adventure-log/*.textile`
- `lore/characters/*.textile`
- `metadata/sync-state.json` (bridge metadata only)

**Repo-only** (never synced to OP):

- `notes/` - GM todos, shelved checklists, scratch (`notes/todo.md`, `notes/character-descriptions-todo.md`, `notes/quick-npc.md`)
- `.cursor/rules/` - agent conventions

**Bridge sync** (companion repo `obsidianportal-git-sync`):

- Pull OP → GitHub → local: `uv run lore-bridge from-op` (needs `LORE_BRIDGE_URL`, `LORE_BRIDGE_API_KEY` in repo `.env`; see `.env.example`)
- After pull: watch for stash/merge conflicts and `op_updated_at` regressions (see below)

## Line endings (CRLF) - important

`.textile` files must use **LF** only (see `.gitattributes`: `*.textile text eol=lf`).

**Why it matters:** Obsidian Portal pulls sometimes introduce **CRLF** in the working tree. Git then shows files as modified when content is unchanged, blocks `git pull --ff-only` / `stash pop`, and creates noisy diffs. Pre-commit hooks also enforce LF (`mixed-line-ending`, on all `.textile` files).

**Proactive behaviour:**

- Before commit/push, check `git status` for `.textile` files that differ only by line endings - normalize and commit explicitly (`chore: normalize line endings in …`) if the user cares about a clean tree.
- After `lore_pull.sh`, stash, or merge: if pull fails with "local changes would be overwritten" but diff looks like whitespace/CRLF, stash or normalize line endings before retrying.
- Do **not** convert Textile to Markdown; OP renders Textile.
- HTML comments must use ASCII `<!--` and `-->`. Smart dashes (`<!-`) break comments and render as visible body text on OP.

## Character page descriptions (`OP_DESCRIPTION`)

- **Non-PCs:** read-aloud prose for first meeting - *"You see…"* - **current** appearance, not founder statuary or civic artwork (players may meet lords before immortality is known).
- **NPC description checklist** (all eight in `OP_DESCRIPTION`): **race**; **skin tone**; **build**; **hair / facial hair** (or equivalent for horned / scaled ancestries); **clothing** — Factors from the relevant `house-*.textile` **Fashion** section; Adjutants show house influence unless they wear a dedicated uniform (e.g. [[The Fulcrum | Fulcrum]] service livery, [[House Meness | Meness]] watch-coat); **how they present** (demeanour / bearing); **how they talk** (pace, register, habits).
- **PCs:** portrait-based or player-provided; D&D Beyond links belong in `OP_BIO`, not as the only description.
- **GM-only lords:** `OP_DESCRIPTION` should work when the page is later made public; avoid Octarion/founder-art framing in the quick-description field.
- Full checklist and tier rollout: `notes/character-descriptions-todo.md` (repo only).

## GM vs player knowledge

- Respect `op_gm_only: true` in frontmatter and `<!-- GM_INFO_START -->` … `<!-- GM_INFO_END -->` blocks.
- **Lore bridge GM blocks** (companion repo `obsidianportal-git-sync`): markers map to Obsidian Portal's single **`game_master_info`** field per page — content between the markers syncs to OP's GM Only box; the rest is public **body**. The bridge parses **only the first** `GM_INFO_START` / `GM_INFO_END` pair. A second pair on the same page is **not** extracted: everything after the first `GM_INFO_END` (including any later markers) stays in the public body on OP. **Use exactly one GM block per page, at the bottom of the file** (after all player-facing prose). On pull, the bridge re-appends that block to the file tail.
- **Player Secrets** (Ascendant OP feature) are **not** in the Obsidian Portal API and **do not sync** via the lore bridge. Never put them in bio/description with `OP_PLAYER_SECRETS` comment markers - they publish as visible body text on OP. Maintain player-secret text in OP's Player Secrets UI; optional GM-only mirror in `GM_INFO` for repo reference.
- When summarising GM notes, label them as GM-only.
- Do not blend GM secrets into player-safe recaps, handouts, or "what the party knows" unless asked.
- If unclear whether output is GM-facing or player-facing, ask.

## Character affiliations and index tags

**Purpose:** stop agents from “helpfully” tagging characters with factions the **party has not learned in play**, which would spoil the Obsidian Portal character index. This is a guardrail when **adding or changing** tags - not a reason to strip lore the user or GM has already established.

- **Player-visible index** (`op_gm_only: false`): `tags` should reflect affiliations the **party currently knows** from play - uniform, introduction, seating, etc. - not secrets inferred from GM wiki prose or `GM_INFO` blocks.
- **Do not add** undercover or unrevealed tags unless the user explicitly asks (e.g. do **not** tag [[:marceline | Marceline]] as Anathemist, merchant spies as their true faction, Embren as Oestra, or Fulcrum staff house ties before shown in session - even if the character page body or GM notes state the truth).
- **Preserve** existing deliberate choices: GM blocks, session bios, and tags the user has set (e.g. [[:cedric | Cedric]] as [[House Meness | Meness]] [[Adjutant | Adjutant]], Tryke/Stegg, City Cats). Do not remove them to “enforce” player knowledge.
- **GM-only pages** (`op_gm_only: true`) may carry full tags for GM index use; still avoid adding spoilery tags to player-visible pages by mistake.
- Unrevealed index affiliations belong in `<!-- GM_INFO_START -->` until revealed in play (e.g. Fulcrum staff → Lithra/Beltus/Grimbolg).
- **OP_DESCRIPTION** / **OP_BIO** on player pages: only what the party has learned; GM truth stays in GM blocks or GM-only pages.
- **Deceased** and **Undead** are state tags for tile styling, not separate index sections (see OP custom CSS below).
- **City Cats** and **Black Cats** when membership is established in play (or on GM-only pages).

### Obsidian Portal - Custom CSS (SSOT)

**Single file:** `notes/obsidian-portal/custom-css.css` - paste entire file into Campaign Settings → Advanced → Custom CSS. Includes CoS grey palette, character index tile borders (Deceased / Undead), `.wonch-timeline-*`, and item wiki tiles. Alternate theme only: `custom-css-cos-theme-safe.css` (not appended).

Index tile borders for state tags live in that file; adjust selectors if Inspect shows different OP classes.

City Cats layout block (after Black Cats; no separate Undead section):

```html
<div class="secondary-heading">CITY CATS</div>
<div class="content-list" data-filter=".tag-city-cats">
  <ul class="large-block-grid-3 small-block-grid-1"></ul>
  <hr>
</div>
```

Extend the **OTHERS** `:not()` chain with `:not(.tag-city-cats)` only (not `.tag-undead` - undead characters stay in their normal buckets).

### Obsidian Portal - Custom JavaScript

**Ascendant-only** — Campaign Settings → Advanced → **Custom JavaScript** (Public). Not synced via the lore bridge; local reference: `notes/obsidian-portal/custom-javascript.js` (paste entire file into OP).

**Live behaviour** (hooks `opJsInitializedEvent`, `ajaxComplete`, `page:load`):

- **VS Code-style heading folds** — wraps `h1`–`h6` sections in `<details class="op-heading-fold">`; `h1` and `h2` open by default (`defaultOpenLevel: 2`). Skips accordions, stat blocks, GM-only boxes, character name headers, and footnote blocks.
- **Footnote relocation** — promotes `<!-- op-footnotes -->` … `<!-- /op-footnotes -->` comment pairs into a `.op-footnotes` div, then moves all footnote blocks to the **end of the page content root** so they are never folded inside a section.

Constraints: visitors may **Deny** custom JS (CSS withheld until Allow); no server-side writes; hook after `opJsInitializedEvent`. Escape hatch: `[campaign-slug].obsidianportal.com/reset-custom-js`.

Local backups: `notes/obsidian-portal/` (grey palette CSS + custom JS).

## Modes of response

- **Lookup**: answer from canon; quote or paraphrase with citations.
- **Speculation**: flag clearly as theory, not established fact.
- **Draft wiki content**: match existing Textile style (frontmatter, `h2.`/`h3.`, blockquotes, accordions).
- **Edits**: suggest or implement only when asked; keep diffs minimal.

## Mechanical vs player-facing wiki content

**Default:** *mechanical* information is **GM-only** unless the user explicitly asks for it in the main body.

**Mechanical** (GM block or `op_gm_only: true` page):

- Species / ancestry **tiers** (Core, Common, Rare, etc.) and pick tables for NPC generation
- Instructions to the GM or to an agent ("when generating…", "plot-only", "not quotas", "do not treat as a pool")
- District **placement** rules for cast composition (which population dominates where for prep)
- Naming nudges, target distributions, and other prep tooling
- Restricted / non-existent lists used to gate random generation

**Player-facing** (main body on public pages):

- In-world sociology and prose — what people in the setting know, see, and remark on
- History, geography, culture, and observable facts the party could learn in play
- Tables that describe the world as characters experience it (e.g. founder depictions on statues)

Use `<!-- GM_INFO_START -->` … `<!-- GM_INFO_END -->` on mixed pages — **one block only, at the file bottom** (see *GM vs player knowledge* above). Whole pages that are prep-only may use `op_gm_only: true` in frontmatter instead.

When splitting content, keep public prose readable without the GM block — agents and the GM still read both.

## Session citations (footnotes)

When wiki or character content ties facts to play or a specific adventure log beat, **do not** use inline `[[Session N: … | …]]` links in prose. Use Textile footnotes instead:

1. Marker in prose: `[1]` immediately **after** sentence-ending punctuation — e.g. `routes.[1]`, not `routes[1].` (same for `?` / `!`). If the citation applies to a whole sentence, place the marker at the end of that sentence. Reuse the same number for the same session.
2. Definition: `fn1. [[Session N: Title | Session N: Title]]` — optional em dash note for what happened there.
3. **Wrapper (required)** — wrap all `fn*` definitions in an **`.op-footnotes`** block so campaign Custom JavaScript can relocate them past heading folds. The block must sit at the **end of the player-facing body** (never inside `GM_INFO`).

   **Character pages** — at the end of `OP_BIO`, immediately before `<!-- GM_INFO_START -->`:

   ```
   <div class="op-footnotes">

   fn1. [[Session N: Title | Session N: Title]]

   </div>
   ```

   **Wiki pages** — immediately before `<!-- GM_INFO_START -->` (or at file end on GM-only pages with no player section). Either:

   - `<div class="op-footnotes">` … `fn*` lines … `</div>` (matches character pages), or
   - `<!-- op-footnotes -->` … `fn*` lines … `<!-- /op-footnotes -->` (comment pair; JS promotes to `.op-footnotes` on render — preferred when the block sits among many `h2.`/`h3.` sections).

   Optional `<hr>` immediately before the wrapper on wiki pages. Do **not** leave bare `fn*` lines outside the wrapper.

4. **Which session to cite:** the log where the party **witnessed** the beat or **learned** the fact — not necessarily the in-world date on the bio heading (e.g. Ostory sabotage deaths → footnote **Session 5** briefing; Cornucopia tour detail → **Session 11**). Skip footnotes for pre-campaign backstory with no log source.

   GM-block prose may reference `[1]` when the matching `fn*` is defined in the player body above.

**Exceptions (keep inline text or links):**

- **Adventure log posts** — they _are_ the session; inline links and headers stay as-is.
- **`the-adventurers.textile` timeline** — the chronology table is an index of sessions; inline log links are intentional.
- **Campaign status lines** — e.g. `_Through Session 11 (date SC)._` on `home-page`, `the-adventurers`, faction clocks; these are “current as of” markers, not scene citations.
- **Bare session numbers in GM meta** — e.g. “What's Changed Since Session 2” as a **heading** (no link needed); footnote the first prose citation in that section instead.

**Proactive check:** when editing wiki or character pages, grep for `[[Session` and `(Session N)` in player body and GM blocks; convert citations that point at adventure logs. Report pages still using inline session links, play-derived `**` bio lines missing `[N]` markers, bare `fn*` lines not wrapped in `.op-footnotes`, or footnote blocks placed inside `GM_INFO`.

## Read-aloud descriptions (wiki vs adventure logs)

**Wiki pages are the authoritative source** for set-piece read-aloud (`bq).` blocks and location descriptions. Adventure logs may carry the same prose for narrative flow at the table, but when editing canon, **update the wiki first** (or together), then align logs to match.

**Do not** introduce snippet/include tooling — copy-and-paste duplication between log and wiki is acceptable; avoid drift through deliberate checks (below).

**Log vs wiki expectations:**

- **Wiki** — stable reference prose; no session-specific beats (who took what, combat outcomes) unless they permanently changed the location.
- **Log** — may add contextual framing ("With Ros needing respite…") or party actions around a shared `bq).` block; the block itself should match the wiki unless the scene *changed* the location in play.
- **Direct contradiction** between log and wiki read-aloud (layout, objects, counts, who is depicted how) should be flagged and resolved — wiki wins unless the user says the log reflects a deliberate in-play change.

**Proactive check (run when editing adventure logs, location wiki pages, or before a lore push):**

1. Scan touched adventure logs for `bq).` blocks describing places that have (or should have) a wiki page.
2. Compare each block to the matching wiki section. Report:
   - **Missing on wiki** — read-aloud exists in log only; suggest copying to wiki.
   - **Missing on log** — wiki has prose the log never used (informational only; not always a problem).
   - **Deviation** — same scene, conflicting details; quote both sides and recommend wiki-aligned fix unless context explains the difference.
3. Priorise locations the party has visited (`osteomantic-archives`, districts, key buildings).

## Adventure log posts (template)

All posts in `lore/wiki/adventure-log/` follow this structure:

**Frontmatter (required):**
- `post_tagline:` — short hook shown on the OP adventure log index (every session).
- `post_time:` — in-game datetime for ordering.
- `name` and `title` — must match (full session title, e.g. `Session 11: Gunpowder, Treason, and Plot`; no placeholder `?` names).

**Body structure:**
1. `h2. Dramatis Personae` — cast list in compact `[accordion]` markup (see `session-1-the-white-dragon.textile`: one line per `[accordion-item]`, no extra indentation).
2. `h2.` top-level scene headings — narrative beats, locations, and day wrappers.
3. `h3.` sub-sections **only where a scene previously had nested structure** (e.g. college rooms under `h2. Fallowhurst College`, house visits under `h2. …split up…`, downtime PCs under `h2. Downtime`). Do not flatten nested beats to `h2.`.
4. Optional timestamp line under each scene heading: `_Morning of the Nth of Enean… ([[The Soulwind Calendar | SC]])_`
5. Prose, optional `bq).` read-aloud blocks.
6. `<!-- GM_INFO_START -->` … `<!-- GM_INFO_END -->` at file bottom **only** when the session has notes that do not belong on a wiki page; otherwise point to the relevant wiki GM section.

**GM blocks on logs:** optional. Prefer wiki pages for location/navigation canon; use log GM blocks for session-only reminders and pointers.

## Wiki page headings

Public body and GM blocks use the same hierarchy:

1. **`h2.`** — major sections (Geography, Catacombs, Personnel, Acts of Sabotage).
2. **`h3.`** — subsections under an `h2.` (Known Factors / Known Adjutants under *Personnel*, individual halls, timeline dates, rank tables).
3. **`h4.`** — only when nested under an `h3.` (e.g. hall names under *Halls of History*).

Do not start the player body with `h3.` or skip levels (`h2.` → `h4.` without an intervening `h3.`). GM-only pages (`op_gm_only: true`) follow the same rule inside their single GM block.

**Great House pages:** party-known officers live under `h2. Personnel` with `h3. Known Factors` and/or `h3. Known Adjutants` (not top-level `h2.`).

## Character pages (template)

**Scaffold (repo only, not synced):** `notes/character-template.textile` — copy to `lore/characters/<op_slug>.textile` for new pages.

Do **not** put a `_template.textile` under `lore/characters/`: the lore bridge publishes all `lore/characters/*.textile` on push to `main`; there is no documented underscore exclude, so a template there would create a junk Character on OP.

All character files in `lore/characters/` share this layout:

**Frontmatter:** `op_slug`, `name`, `title`, `op_gm_only`, `is_player_character`, `tags` (party-known affiliations only on public pages), optional `avatar_url`.

**Body (in order):**

1. `<!-- OP_DESCRIPTION -->` — read-aloud *"You see…"* for non-PCs; portrait-based or player-provided for PCs. Never empty on public NPCs the party has met.
2. `<!-- OP_BIO -->` — chronological play history and in-world facts the party knows; wiki links; no GM secrets.
3. `<!-- GM_INFO_START -->` … `<!-- GM_INFO_END -->` — plot role, investigative footprints, prep notes, and **stat blocks**. Use `h2.` / `h3.` like wiki pages. Omit the block only when there is genuinely no GM-only content.

**Do not** use `h2.`/`h3.` in `OP_DESCRIPTION` except optional `h3. Key Items` on lords and PCs. Headings belong in `OP_BIO` (rare) or `GM_INFO`.

**Clothing:** Great House **Factors** — dress from that house's Fashion section (`lore/wiki/wiki/house-*.textile`). **Adjutants** — house colours and details in practical cuts (apron, tool belt, throat-pin) unless they wear an institutional uniform ([[The Fulcrum | Fulcrum]] service livery, [[House Meness | Meness]] watch-coat). Fulcrum staff share pale marble-grey tunics with the eight-pointed star at the collar (table canon until a wiki entry exists).

### Founders (exception)

Octarion / Great House founder pages (`op_gm_only: true`):

- **No combat stat blocks** — founders are not encounter stat lines.
- **`OP_DESCRIPTION`** — current appearance when the party might meet them (not founder-statuary framing).
- **`OP_BIO`** — often empty; chronology lives on house and history wiki pages.
- **`GM_INFO`** — full lore, afflictions, `h2. Depictions` for civic art, key items in prose. Reference: `lord-ablas-oestra.textile`.

Hexine Circle Factors use `h2. Spies lead` in `GM_INFO` for their investigation accordion quote (see `hielaman.textile`, `commander-locke.textile`).

### GM block headings (`h2.` vocabulary)

Use Textile `h2.` inside the single `GM_INFO` block. Pick what applies; omit unused sections.

| Heading | When to use | Examples |
|---------|-------------|----------|
| **Spies lead** | Hexine Circle Factor — paste `bq).` quote from `the-investigation.textile` | `hielaman.textile`, `emissary-halan.textile` |
| **Prep** | Session notes, motives, how they react to the Wonch | `cedric.textile`, `nort.textile` |
| **True role** | Cover identity or hidden assignment | `cedric.textile` |
| **Black Cats link** | Confirmed syndicate tie (not player-facing until revealed) | `chuggaz.textile` |
| **Depictions** | Founder civic art, statuary, propaganda (founders only) | `lord-ablas-oestra.textile` |
| **Backstory** / **History** | Deep lore when bio is intentionally thin | PCs, associates |
| **Stat block** | Combat NPCs — precede `<div class="stat-block">` | `pthul.textile`, `embren-oestra.textile` |
| **Player secret** | Mirror of OP Player Secrets UI (optional; not API-synced) | `nakoma-deathwalker-mor-got-ha.textile` |

Do not invent duplicate spy-lead headings (`Spies lead:` vs `Spies Lead`); use **`h2. Spies lead`** exactly.

### Bio dating

Chronological `OP_BIO` entries use dated headings from the adventure logs:

`* *29th of Enean, year 4218 ([[The Soulwind Calendar | SC]])*`

followed by `**` event lines. One-line role intro (rank + house) may precede the first date block. **Every in-play event drawn from an adventure log must sit under the log's dated heading** — do not lump events under the wrong day. **Footnote** each play-derived `**` line per *Session citations (footnotes)* — cite the session where the party learned or witnessed the beat, then add `fn*` definitions inside `<div class="op-footnotes">` at the end of `OP_BIO`.

### DM stat blocks (GM block only)

Combat stats belong in `GM_INFO`, never in `OP_DESCRIPTION` or `OP_BIO`. Use a `<div class="stat-block">` wrapper so campaign Custom CSS applies (`notes/obsidian-portal/custom-css.css`). Do not use the unstyled `statname` / `contenteditable` OP export markup unless you also add matching CSS.

Reference implementations: `lore/characters/pthul.textile`, `lore/characters/embren-oestra.textile`.

**Skeleton:**

```html
<div class="stat-block">
<h3>Name</h3>
<p><em>Size type, alignment</em></p>
<p><strong>Armor Class</strong> …<br>
<strong>Hit Points</strong> …<br>
<strong>Speed</strong> …<br>
<strong>Initiative</strong> …</p>
<hr>
<table>
    <tr><th>STR</th><th>DEX</th><th>CON</th><th>INT</th><th>WIS</th><th>CHA</th></tr>
    <tr><td>…</td><td>…</td><td>…</td><td>…</td><td>…</td><td>…</td></tr>
</table>
<hr>
<p><strong>Senses</strong> …<br>
<strong>Languages</strong> …<br>
<strong>Challenge</strong> …</p>
<hr>
<h4>Actions</h4>
<p><strong>Attack name.</strong> <em>Melee Weapon Attack:</em> +X to hit, … <em>Hit:</em> … damage.</p>
</div>
```

Optional *Traits*, *Reactions*, and *Legendary Actions* sections use `<p><strong>Name.</strong> …</p>` or `<h4>` subheadings inside the same `.stat-block` div. Other GM prose may precede or follow the stat block.

